snippet.textDisplay: Hope this serves a good lesson for Djokovic. As a role model to many young tennis players - particularly his own peeps, who really look up to him, Djokovic should learn to uphold world's no.1 standard sportsmanship, which includes respecting the rules and law anywhere he goes. What Djokovic, his family and all the people they sent to the street and social media in order to pressure the Australian authorities have shown is nothing but arrogance and disrespect. He had the option to stick up to his principles of not getting vaxxed and opt out from the AO this summer. However, he chose to come to the game but play by his own rules. Yes, the government's decision was made in the public interest - the public wants to see fairness and see no celebrity should think they are special enough to act above our law. Listen to the big tennis community and we can barely hear any big names coming forward to support Djokovic or showing the slightest sympathy for his stunt, because all the big names know exactly what a character Djokovic is. Time to pack up and go home for some reflection, Djoko. Hold a press conference and make a decent apology - and you might be allowed to compete in the next AO.

Assuming Novax Djocovid really did test positive on 16 December, then he has broken a number of laws which would implicate him criminally:
1. He went out in public in Serbia the next day and spread the virus around
2. He travelled to Spain and lied to their Border Security by producing a magically negative PCR result
3. He proceeded to have multiple training sessions and have two interviews in Spain without warning anyone he was positive
4. He returned to Belgrade to party and spread the virus to young children
5. He reported to Australia that he did not travel for 14 days when he had just travelled to Spain
6. When he had provided a negative test to Spain just days ago, he somehow produced a positive result to Australia to "exempt" him from vaccination 
7. Even assuming he was indeed positive, ATAGI (Australia's vaccination board) states "people who have previously had COVID-19 and not received a vaccine dose are not considered fully vaccinated. Such people are not proved for quarantine-free entry, regardless of whether they have received foreign vaccination exemptions”
There is absolutely no reason why Novax should be allowed into Australia, and Serbia and Spain should follow with further investigations

snippet.textDisplay: The news like to sensationalise things. Why was the visa granted if not vaccinated? That is because visas can be granted if the VISA requirements are met (which they were). What wasn't met was the condition of ENTRY. Why was he allowed to board? Simply human error at check-in. Do you know how many countries change COVID travel rules everyday? Mistakes do happen in the end. His travel declaration was filled by his agent incorrectly by mistake (HUMAN error). Newflash, the travel declaration filling responsibility is of the traveller, so he cannot deflect blame on that. So to sum up, Novak satisfied the conditions of getting a visa but not entering Australia. Think of it this way, a criminal may not declare their criminal record and obtain a visa, but on the border their criminal past may be found out. Of course then they would be deported if they don't meet the conditions of entry and the visa cancelled. Novak still has special treatment as most deported people don't get to reach a judge.
